# Records

- Each time you write a record to a sequential access file, you
  write the fields that make up the record, one after the other

\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[scale=0.2]{figures/ch06-fig-6-19-records-file}
\label{fig:ch05-fig-6-19-records-file}
\caption{Records in a file \parencite[pg.351]{gaddis-2021}}
\end{figure}

# Application to Process Records

- When working with records (like a database), typically the following
  operations all need to be implemented
  - Add a record
  - Display records (generate reports)
  - Search for a specific record
  - Modify / update a record
  - Delete a record


# Exceptions (1 of 3)

::: columns
:::: {.column width=50%}
- **Exception**: error that occurs while a program is running
  - Usually causes program to abruptly halt
  - Can sometimes continue from an exception, sometimes cannot
- **Traceback**: error message that gives information regarding
  line numbers that caused the exception
  - Indicates the type of exception and brief description of the error
    that caused exception to be raised

::::
:::: {.column width=50%}
## Exceptions

An exception is an error that occurs while a program is running, causing
the program to abruptly halt.  You can use the `try / except` statement
in Python to gracefully handle exceptions when anticipated or expected
in your code.
::::
:::

# Exceptions (2 of 3)

- Some (many?) exceptions can be prevented by careful coding
  - Example: input validation
  - Usually involve a simple decision construct
- Some exceptions cannot be avoided by careful coding
  - Examples
    - Trying to convert non-numeric string to an integer
    - Trying to open for reading a file that doesn't exist

# Exceptions (3 of 3)

- **Exception handler**: code that responds when exceptions are raised
  and prevents program from stopping
  - In Python, written as `try / except ` statement
  - **Try block**: statements that can potentially raise a (particular
    type of) exception
  - **Handler**: statements contained in `except` block that run if 
    exception is raised in the `try` block
  - If statement in try block raises exception
    - Handler immediately following `except` clause executes
    - Continue program after `try / except` statement
  - Other exceptions:
    - Program halts with traceback error message
  - If no exception is raised, handlers are skipped

```{python, evaluate=False}
try:
    statement
    statement
except exceptionName:
    statement
```

# Handling Multiple Exceptions

- Often code in `try` block can throw more than one type of exception
  - Need to write `except` clause for each type of exception that
    needs to be handled

- An `except` clause that does not list a specific exception will handle
  any exception that is raised in the `try` block
  - Should always be last in a series of `except` clauses
  - Usually a **BAD** code smell, should usually not try and handle any
    and all problems, even if unexpected

# Displaying an Exception's Default Error Message

- Exception object: object created in memory when an exception is thrown
  - Usually contains default error message pertaining to the exception
  - Can assign the exception object to a variable in an `except` clause
    - Example: `except ValueError as err:`
  - Can pass exception object variable to `print()` function to 
    display the default error message

# The `else` Clause

- `try / except` statement may include an optional `else` clause, which
  appears after all the `except` clauses
  - Aligned with `try` and `except` clauses
  - Syntax similar to `else` clause in decision structure
  - `Else suite`: block of statements executed after statement in `try`
    block, only if no exceptions were raised
    - If exception was raised, the `else` suite is skipped

# The `finally` Clause

- `try / except` statement may include an optional `finally` clause, which
  appears after all the except clauses
  - Aligned with `try` and `except` clauses
  - Finally suite: block of statements after the `finally` clause
    - Executes whether an exception occurs or not
    - Purpose is to perform cleanup before exiting

# Summary

- A **Record** is a set of data that describes one item
  - This is a classic CS concept, see [User-Defined Type](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Record_(computer_science)) \parencite{wikipedia-record-2026}
  - A record is composed of **Field**s, single pieces of data that compose the record
- Using a sequential file, you have to read all records into memory to add and modify, and write back whole file when done.
- **Exception**s are errors that occur while a program is running
- In Python you can use `try / except` statements to try and gracefully
  exceptions raised by programs


